Claims Claims 1. A device to facilitate an assessment of a characteristic of a bone of a subject, the device comprising: a movable tapper to deliver a measured load force as an impact force to a first region of a bone of a subject; a load source to generate a motive force and arranged to transmit the motive force to the tapper; a quantitative load unit coupled to the load source to provide a magnitude of the impact force generated by the tapper is quantitatively pre-determined prior to delivery of the impact force to the bone via the tapper. 2. The device as claimed in claim 1 wherein the load unit comprises any one or a combination of the following set of: Â· a load cell connected electronically to the load source and/or the tapper; â¢ a computer and/or a processor connected electronically to the load source and/or the tapper. 3. The device as claimed in claims 1 or 2 wherein the load unit is configured to set and/or determine a supply voltage and/or a duration of the supply voltage at the load source to provide the quantitative pre-determined magnitude of the impact force prior to delivery by the tapper. 4. The device as claimed in any preceding claim wherein the load source comprises any one of: â¢ an electric motor; â¢ a solenoid. 5. The device as claimed in any preceding claim wherein the load source is configured to create a repeating predefined motive force to be delivered to the subject by the tapper as a series of impulse strikes. 6. The device as claimed in any preceding claim wherein the load unit is a load cell coupled to the load source and the tapper such that the load cell is positioned intermediate the load source and the tapper. 7. The device as claimed in any preceding claim wherein the load unit is an electronic component configured to identify a voltage applied to the load source. 8. The device as claimed in any preceding claim further comprising a control module to control delivery of an operational parameter to the load source. 9. The device as claimed in claim 8 wherein the control module comprises a processor, a computer, software and a data storage utility. 10. The device as claimed in claim 8 or 9 wherein the operational parameter comprises any one or a combination of the following set of: â¢ a voltage â¢ an amplitude of excitation â¢ a time period duration of a motive force pulse â¢ a time period between respective motive force pulses. 11. The device as claimed in claim 8 or 9 wherein the load source via the control module is configured to provide a variation of a magnitude of the motive force to selectively change a magnitude of the impact force to be delivered to the subject by the tapper. 12. The device as claimed in any preceding claim further comprising a tilt indicator to output an indication of an inclination of the device relative to a horizontal plane. 13. The device as claimed in any preceding claim further comprising a biased return actuator acting on at least a region of the tapper to provide a return force to move the tapper in a reverse direction relative to a forward direction of the tapper that delivers the impact force. 14. The device as claimed in claim 9 wherein the software is configured to determine, identify, change and/or record a voltage applied by the power source to the load source. 15. The device as claimed in any preceding claim further comprising at least one mechanical adjuster to change a position of the tapper at the device to provide variation of the magnitude of the impact force delivered to the bone by the tapper. 16. Assessment apparatus to facilitate an assessment of a characteristic of a bone of a subject, the apparatus comprising: a device as claimed in any preceding claim; at least one vibration sensor positionable at at least one second region of the bone separated from the first region to identify a vibration signal induced in the bone and transmitted through the bone from the first region to the second region. 17. The apparatus as claimed in claim 16 wherein the vibration sensor comprises any one or a combination of the following set of: â¢ a microphonic based sensor; â¢ a piezoelectric based microphonic sensor; Â· a ceramic based microphone; â¢ a capacitor based sensor; â¢ a film capacitor based sensor comprising a dielectric material; â¢ an air or glass dielectric based capacitor sensor; â¢ at least one piezoelectric sensor. 18. The apparatus as claimed in claims 16 or 17 further comprising any one or a combination of: a processor, a computer, software, and a data storage facility. 19. The apparatus as claimed in any one of claims 16 to 18 further comprising a vibration signal amplifier to amplify the vibration signal obtained from the vibration sensor. 20. The apparatus as claimed in any one of claims 16 to 19 further comprising a signal frequency low pass and high pass filter to truncate a frequency of the vibration signal according to predetermined cut-off frequencies. 21. The apparatus as claimed in any one of claims 16 to 20 further comprising a signal analogue to digital converter to convert an analogue vibration signal to a digital vibration signal. 22. The apparatus as claimed in claim 21 wherein the analogue to the digital converter is configured for operation and data acquisition at a sample rate in the range 50 kHz to 150 kHz. 23. The apparatus as claimed in any one of claims 16 to 21 further comprising vibration signal data analysis software to interrogate and/or process the vibration signal and output at least one said characteristic of the bone. 24. The apparatus as claimed in any one of claims 16 to 23 comprising a plurality of vibration sensors positioned respectively at different regions of the bone relative to one another and the first region. 25. The apparatus as claimed in any one of claims 16 to 24 comprising at least one support having a first portion to support in touching contact the first region of the bone of the subject and a second portion to support in touching contact the second region of the bone of the subject, the tapper mounted at the support at the first portion and the vibration sensor mounted at the support at the second portion. 26. A method of inducing and recording vibration within a bone of a subject comprising: i) delivering an impact force to a first region of the bone using a tapper, a magnitude of the impact force being quantitatively pre-determined prior to delivery; ii) allowing an induced vibration signal to be transmitted through the bone; 

 iii) recording a vibration response signal at at least one second region of the bone positionally spaced from the first region using at least one vibration sensor. 27. The method as claimed in claim 26 further comprising the step of conditioning the vibration response signal using an amplification and filtering device. 28. The method as claimed in claims 26 or 27 further comprising converting the vibration response signal using an analogue to digital converter. 29. The method as claims in any one of claims 26 to 28 further comprising storing data based on the vibration response signal within a data storage facility. 30. The method as claimed in any one of claims 26 to 29 wherein the vibration sensor comprises any one or a combination of the following set of: â¢ a microphonic based sensor; â¢ a piezoelectric based microphonic sensor; â¢ a ceramic based microphone; â¢ a capacitor based sensor; â¢ a film capacitor based sensor comprising a dielectric material; â¢ an air or glass dielectric based capacitor sensor; â¢ at least one piezoelectric sensor. 31. The method as claimed in any one of claims 26 to 30 wherein the magnitude of the impact force is quantitatively pre-determined prior to delivery using a quantitative load unit coupled electronically to a load source that is in turn coupled electronically to the tapper. 32. A method of estimating a characteristic of a bone of a test subject comprising: â¢ pre-processing data of at least one induced vibration response signal obtained at a region of the bone of the test subject via a vibration sensor to extract component part features of said signal; 

 processing the component part features by principal component analysis to obtain a set of principal components of said signal; using a model to apply the principal components to a reference library containing a plurality of sets of principal components of induced vibration response signals obtained from a plurality of reference subjects, the reference library further comprising at least one characteristic of a bone and/or at least one characteristic of the subject of each of the respective reference subjects; obtaining from the model an estimate of the characteristic of the bone of the test subject. 33. The method as claimed in claim 32 wherein the step of pre-processing the data comprises transforming the data by at least one or a combination of the following set of: â¢ time domain analysis Â· frequency domain analysis. 34. The method as claimed in claim 33 wherein the frequency domain analysis comprises any one or a combination of the following set of: â¢ Fourier transformation decomposition Â· wavelet transformation decomposition â¢ multi-resolution decomposition. 35. The method as claimed in any one of claims 32 to 34 wherein the at least one characteristic of the subject within the reference library comprises data relating to a set of physical characteristics of each reference subject including any one or a combination of the following set: â¢ age â¢ gender â¢ height Â· weight â¢ body mass index â¢ length of bone to be analysed. 36. The method as claimed in any one of claims 32 to 35 wherein the at least one characteristic of the bone of each of the reference subjects comprises a bone mineral density derived or obtained via a reference analytical measurement method. 37. A method as claimed in any one of claims 32 to 36 wherein the step of using the model to apply the principal components to the reference library comprises any one or a combination of the following set of: â¢ regression analysis Â· artificial neural network analysis â¢ discriminant analysis â¢ clustering analysis. 38. The method as claimed in any one of claims 32 to 37 wherein the step of pre- processing the data further comprises selecting a part of the data of the vibration response signal from which to extract the component part features. 39. The method as claimed in any one of claims 32 to 38 wherein the at least one characteristic of the bone of each of the reference subject comprises any one or a combination of the following set: â¢ a quantitative value corresponding to an extent to which a prosthetic is secured to a bone of the reference subject; â¢ a quantitative value that corresponds to an extent to which a bone of the reference subject is fractured; wherein the method comprises estimating an extent to which: â¢ a prosthetic is secured to the bone of the test subject; or â¢ the bone of the test subject is fractured. 40. A method of assessing at least one characteristic of a bone of a subject comprising: at a first time period inducing and recording vibration within the bone via the steps of i), ii) and iii) of claim 26; 

 repeating the steps i), ii) and iii) of claim 26 at a second time period later than the first time period; comparing the vibration response signals obtained at the first and second time periods to identify differences in the respective vibration response signals. 41. The method as claimed in claim 40 wherein the step of comparing the vibration response signals involves comparing the vibration response signals prior to processing the data of the vibration response signals to obtain component part features or principal components of the vibration response signals or following said processing of said vibration response signals to obtain the component part features or the principal components. 42. A network to facilitate assessment of at least one characteristic of a bone of test subjects comprising: a central hub having a processor, software, at least one communication module and a data storage facility; a reference library containing sets of principal components of induced vibration response signals obtained from a plurality of reference subjects in addition to at least one characteristic of the bone and/or at least one characteristic of the subject of each of the respective reference subjects; a plurality of bone characteristic assessment devices, each device having a movable tapper, a load source and a quantitative load unit coupled to the load source to provide a magnitude of an impact force generated by the tapper is a quantitative predetermined value prior to delivery of the impact force to the bone of each test subject by the tapper, each device further comprising a vibration sensor to monitor a vibration response signal induced in the bone by the tapper; wherein the devices are provided for data communication with the hub for exchange of data relating to the reference library and/or data based on the respective vibration response signals of respective test subjects. 43. The network as claimed in claim 42 wherein the vibration sensor comprises any one of or a combination of the following set of: â¢ a microphonic based sensor; 

 a piezoelectric based microphonic sensor; a ceramic based microphone; a capacitor based sensor; a film capacitor based sensor comprising a dielectric material an air or glass dielectric based capacitor sensor; at least one piezoelectric sensor.
